Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve the @aubergine{1} lengthways, keeping the stem attached. Score the flesh
deeply in a criss-cross pattern, taking care not to cut through the skin. Put
the aubergine halves, skin-side down, onto a large lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle
with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

When the oven is hot, roast the aubergine on the top shelf until golden brown
and soft (you should be able to mash the flesh), ~{25-28%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

== Béchamel ==

Meanwhile, heat a #medium saucepan{} on medium heat.

Melt in the @butter{10%g}, then add the @plain flour{1%tbsp} and cook, stirring
occasionally for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Gradually add the @milk{150%ml}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, and cook,
stirring occasionally until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once thickened, add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g} until melted -
you want the béchamel to be thick and spoonable.

Transfer your béchamel to a #small bowl{} and set aside for later. Clean out the
pan.

== Toasted Tomato Bulgur ==

Boil a half-full #kettle{}. Return the (now empty) #saucepan{} on medium high
heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, stirring regularly, until lightly
toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch it like a hawk as it can burn easily.

Next, stir in the @tomato puree{30%g} and stir-fry until the bulgur is coated,
~{1-2%minutes}.

Pour in the @water for the bulgur{220%ml}, stir in the @chicken stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil. Simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for
~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

== Lamb Filling ==

Meanwhile, heat a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.
Use #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the garlic and fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir through the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @red wine stock paste{28%g},
@ground cinnamon{1%sachet}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the sauce{50%ml}. Bring
the sauce to a boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened,
~{4-5%minutes}.

== Assembly ==

Meanwhile, once you have removed your aubergines from the oven, turn on your
#grill{} to its highest temperature.

Using a #fork{}, mash the flesh of the aubergine until soft.

Spoon your lamb mixture into your aubergine.

> TIP: Don't overfill it - keep any remaining sauce for later.

Spoon over your béchamel and grill until golden and bubbling,
~{4-5%minutes}.

== To Serve ==

Fluff up your bulgur with a fork and stir through any remaining lamb mince and
sauce.

Transfer your aubergine papoutsakia to your #serving plates{} and serve with your
bulgur and @wild rocket{20%g} alongside.

Drizzle some @olive oil{} over the rocket to finish.

Enjoy!